Version 0.4. Reworked sessions.

Major refactoring of sessions. An httpkom session is now more like a
LysKOM session, which is just a connection to the LysKOM server. You
need to first create a session before you can login, but you can also
logout and login in again without having to re-create the
session. This is a first step towards supporting multiple servers and
multiple sessions (not requiring cookies).
Documentation fixes.

Updating version to 0.7.

Stop using kom.CachedUserConnection because the no_unread cache causes an infinite recursion loop. The cah_new_text method tries to update items that aren't in the cache (and the Cache class doesn't have any method for checking if an item is in the cache or not). We didn't really use any of the functionality anyway, so CachedConnection is enough.
Only fetch read ranges when asked for, to reduce number of work. This means that we don't know number of unread.

Fixed get_unread_texts_from_membership. It didn't update the first local text to get mapping for then iterating over the gaps between the read ranges. Made more explicit loop variables and better handling of if there is more to fetch.

Fix Flask app initialization to work correctly by requiring explicit init.

When httpkom.main was added the initialization order was broken, as calling
httpkom.main would always import httpkom.__init__ and initialize
the Flask app object. The function httpkom.main.run_http_server() assumed
it was possible to modify the os.environ HTTPKOM_SETTINGS variable and
get the expected effect, but it actually didn't have any effect as the app
object was already initialized.
